    id: "mod-5",
    number: 5,
    title: "Reconnaissance and OSINT",
    description: "Passive and active recon, Google dorks, metadata, and subdomains.",
    track: "offensive",
    labTitle: "Target Recon Scenario",
    labDescription: "Choose recon techniques interactively to investigate a target domain.",
    lessons: [
      { title: "Passive Reconnaissance", content: "Information gathering without interacting directly with the target:\n\n**WHOIS:** Domain registration info\n**Passive DNS:** Historical DNS resolutions\n**Shodan/Censys:** Exposed internet devices\n**Google Dorks:** Advanced Google searches\n**Social media:** LinkedIn, GitHub (code leaks)\n**Wayback Machine:** Old site versions\n\nPassive recon is legal because it uses public information.\n\nPassive recon helps understand the target without generating alerts. Ideal for planning and initial mapping.\n\nCombine sources to reduce bias: public records, CT logs, public repos, and historical data.\n\nPractical example: review the organization’s public GitHub and look for keys or internal URLs in old commits.\n\nStep by step:\n1. Collect public data (WHOIS, CT logs).\n2. Correlate names, emails, and infrastructure.\n3. Remove false positives and document findings." },
      { title: "Active Reconnaissance", content: "Direct interaction with the target (requires authorization):\n\n```bash\n# Port scanning\nnmap -sV -sC -A target.com\n\n# Directory enumeration\ngobuster dir -u http://target.com -w wordlist.txt\n\n# Banner grabbing\nnc -nv target.com 80\ncurl -I http://target.com\n```\n\nActive recon produces detectable traffic and can be unauthorized without permission.\n\nEven with authorization, use **rate limits** to avoid downtime. Document everything for traceability.\n\nCritical environments require test windows and ops communication.\n\nPractical example: run `nmap -sV -p 80,443` in the authorized window and record generated traffic.\n\nStep by step:\n1. Confirm authorized scope and window.\n2. Run scans with rate limits.\n3. Record traffic and results." },
      { title: "Advanced Google Dorks", content: "Google dorks are advanced queries to find sensitive info:\n\n```\nsite:target.com filetype:pdf\nsite:target.com inurl:admin\nsite:target.com intitle:\"index of\"\nsite:target.com ext:sql | ext:db | ext:log\ninurl:\"wp-config.php\" \"DB_PASSWORD\"\n```\n\nDatabases like **Google Hacking Database (GHDB)** catalog thousands of useful dorks.\n\nUse dorks carefully and validate results: old files may contain sensitive data that should no longer be public.\n\nBuild a standard dork list by industry (finance, healthcare, education) to speed investigations.\n\nPractical example: use `site:target.com ext:log` to locate exposed logs and verify if they contain sensitive data.\n\nStep by step:\n1. Use dorks by sensitive file type.\n2. Manually validate relevant results.\n3. Document URLs and evidence." },
      { title: "Metadata Extraction", content: "Files contain revealing metadata:\n\n**ExifTool:** Extracts metadata from images, PDFs, documents\n```bash\nexiftool documento.pdf\nexiftool -a -G imagem.jpg\n```\n\nMetadata can reveal: usernames, software used, internal paths, GPS coordinates, creation/modification dates.\n\n**FOCA** is a tool for mass metadata extraction from domains.\n\nBeyond documents, image metadata can reveal **location** and **devices**. Useful in OSINT and forensics.\n\nAlways check privacy policy before collecting and disclosing metadata.\n\nPractical example: download public PDFs and use `exiftool` to find usernames and software versions.\n\nStep by step:\n1. Download public documents from a domain.\n2. Extract metadata with ExifTool.\n3. List users and software versions." },
      { title: "Subdomain Discovery", content: "Subdomains often host less protected services:\n\n```bash\n# Passive enumeration\nsubfinder -d target.com\namass enum -passive -d target.com\n\n# Brute force\ngobuster dns -d target.com -w subdomains.txt\n\n# Certificate Transparency\ncurl 'https://crt.sh/?q=%.target.com&output=json' | jq '.[] | .name_value'\n```\n\n**Subdomain takeover:** When a subdomain points to an unused service, attackers can take control.\n\nAfter discovery, validate services with `httpx` and categorize by criticality. Many incidents stem from forgotten staging environments.\n\nMaintain a live inventory to detect regressions and new exposures.\n\nPractical example: combine `subfinder` with `crt.sh` and then check HTTP to identify staging environments.\n\nStep by step:\n1. Combine passive sources and CT.\n2. Validate HTTP/HTTPS.\n3. Classify by criticality and environment." },
    ],
